North Carolina Drivers: Why Your Auto Insurance Rates Might Go Up After a Comprehensive Claim (Even With Zero Points!)

It's a common source of confusion. We'll break down the facts about comprehensive claims and their impact on your premiums.

By Bill Layne • Published on 2025-10-22

Share:

It's a scenario we see all the time here at our Elkin agency. A driver from Raleigh is heading to the mountains for the weekend, and a rock flies up and cracks their windshield. Or maybe a hailstorm sweeps through Charlotte, leaving dents on the hood. You file a comprehensive claim, your car gets fixed, and you're told there are no insurance points. Case closed, right? Then your renewal arrives, and you're shocked to see a higher premium. This leads to the big question we hear from drivers across the state: "Why did I see a comprehensive claim rate increase in NC if I didn't get any points?"

This is a perfectly valid question, and the answer lies in the difference between North Carolina's "points" system and your insurance carrier's internal risk assessment. Let’s clear up the confusion.

The Myth of "No-Fault, No-Foul" 💡

In North Carolina, the Safe Driver Incentive Plan (SDIP) assigns points for at-fault accidents and moving violations. These points directly and predictably increase your insurance rates. A comprehensive claim—for things like theft, vandalism, hitting a deer, hail, or a cracked windshield—is considered a "no-fault" claim. This means you will not receive any SDIP points for it.

However, your insurance carrier still sees the claim. While it doesn't carry the same weight as an at-fault collision, it does become part of your claims history. Insurers use this history to build a picture of your overall risk profile. And that's where the potential for a rate increase comes in.

So, Why Did My Rate Go Up? 📈

Even without points, a comprehensive claim can influence your premium for several key reasons. It's rarely one single factor, but often a combination of these:

  • Claim Frequency and Severity: One small claim for a windshield repair might not move the needle much. But multiple comprehensive claims within a few years—say, hitting a deer on the Blue Ridge Parkway one year and flood damage from a coastal hurricane the next—paints a picture of higher risk. Your location and the types of claims common there (like hail in the Piedmont) also play a role.
  • Loss of a "Claims-Free" Discount: This is the most common culprit. Many North Carolina drivers benefit from a significant "claims-free" or "good driver" discount without even realizing it. Filing any claim, even a no-fault comprehensive one, can cause you to lose that discount at your next renewal, resulting in a higher premium.
  • Overall Rate Adjustments in Your Area: Sometimes, the rate increase has less to do with you individually and more to do with everyone around you. If an insurance company experiences a surge of claims in a specific area (e.g., massive hail damage across the Triangle or hurricane damage on the Outer Banks), they may adjust rates for all policyholders in that territory to cover the increased risk.
  • Carrier-Specific Guidelines: Every insurance company has its own complex algorithm for calculating risk. Some carriers are more forgiving of comprehensive claims than others. What might trigger a small increase with one company could trigger a larger one—or none at all—with another.

Navigating North Carolina's SDIP and Your Policy ✅

It's vital to understand that the North Carolina Safe Driver Incentive Plan is a state-regulated system. It clearly defines what constitutes a "chargeable accident." A comprehensive claim does not fall into this category. For official details, you can always refer to resources from the North Carolina Department of Insurance (NCDOI). They provide the authoritative breakdown of how points are assigned.

The key takeaway is this: SDIP points are separate from your carrier's internal risk assessment. Not getting points is great, but it doesn't guarantee your rate will stay the same.

What Can You Do About It?

Feeling a bit powerless? Don't be. You have several options to manage your auto insurance costs:

  • Assess the Damage: Before filing a small claim, get a quote for the repair. If the cost is only slightly more than your deductible, it might be cheaper in the long run to pay out-of-pocket and preserve your claims-free discount.
  • Review Your Deductible: Consider a higher comprehensive deductible. A higher deductible means a lower premium. Just make sure you can comfortably afford to pay it if you need to file a claim.
  • Ask About Claim Forgiveness: Some carriers offer an "accident forgiveness" or "claim forgiveness" endorsement. It might add a small cost to your policy, but it can prevent your rates from rising after your first claim.
  • Shop Around: This is the most powerful tool you have. Since every company weighs claims differently, what causes a rate hike at one insurer may not at another. As an independent agency, we can compare rates from multiple top carriers to find the best fit for your situation.

Frequently Asked Questions

Does one comprehensive claim always raise insurance rates in North Carolina?

Not always. A single, minor comprehensive claim might have no impact, especially if you have a long history with no claims. However, it can affect your premium by causing the loss of a "claims-free" discount. The impact depends heavily on your specific insurance carrier, your claims history, and the cost of the claim.

Is it ever worth it to NOT file a comprehensive claim?

Yes, absolutely. If the cost to repair the damage is less than or close to your comprehensive deductible, it's almost always better to pay out-of-pocket. This keeps a claim off your record, which helps you maintain any claims-free discounts and a lower risk profile with your insurer.

How is a comprehensive claim different from a collision claim for my rates?

A collision claim is for when your vehicle collides with another object (like a car, pole, or fence) and is usually considered your fault, resulting in SDIP points and a significant rate increase. A comprehensive claim is for "other than collision" events like theft, fire, animal strikes, or weather damage. It does not add SDIP points but can still influence your rate based on your carrier's risk assessment and your claims frequency.
